In [ ]:
# Path to test directory
test_data_dir = "/wildlife-classification/data/test"
# Path to train directory
train_data_dir = "/wildlife-classification/data/train"

First we are getting all the class names using the os.listdir() method. After that we iterate through the class names to firstly get the train and test image counts. We then get the total image counts and this is used to calculate the test and train percentages for each class. We then add it to a data frame and plot it to show the distribution of test and train images for all the classes.

In [ ]:
# Get the list of class names
class_names = os.listdir(train_data_dir)

# Create a Pandas DataFrame
df = pd.DataFrame(columns=["class_name", "test_percent", "train_percent"])

# Iterate over the class names
for name in class_names:

    # Get the number of test images
    test_image_count = len(os.listdir(os.path.join(test_data_dir, name)))

    # Get the number of train images
    train_image_count = len(os.listdir(os.path.join(train_data_dir, name)))

    # Get the total number of images
    total_image_count = test_image_count + train_image_count

    # Calculate the test percentage
    test_percent = round((test_image_count / total_image_count) * 100, 2)

    # Calculate the train percentage
    train_percent = round((train_image_count / total_image_count) * 100, 2)

    # Add the data to the DataFrame
    df = pd.concat([df, pd.DataFrame({"class_name": name, "test_percent": test_percent, "train_percent": train_percent}, index=[name])])


# Plot the data
df.plot(
    kind="barh",
    stacked=True,
    figsize=(
        10,
        80,
    ),
    colormap="tab10",
    title="Distribution of Test and Train Images",
    xlabel="Percentage",
    ylabel="Class Name",
    legend=True,
)

Here, we are setting variables for ANIMAL_TYPES which is the number of classes in the dataset. Rather than hardcoding, it's better to get the length of the class_names. We also set the IMAGE_SIZE to [244,244]

In [ ]:
ANIMAL_TYPES = len(class_names)
IMAGE_SIZE = [224, 224]

We are declaring the architecture and hyper-parameters for the first model here.

We have 3 layers which we are freezing. Firstly we get the base model with pre-trained weights from the imagenet set and set the input shape as 224x224. The subsequent lines define additional layers and connections to the base model. The flatten layer converts the output of the base model into a 1D feature vector. The dropout layer randomly sets a fraction (50%) of the input units to 0 at each update during training, which helps prevent overfitting. The output layer is a dense layer with softmax activation, producing probabilities for each class.

In [ ]:
with tf.device('/gpu:0'):
    INCEPTION_FREEZE_LAYERS = 3
    
    inception_resnet_base_model = InceptionResNetV2(include_top=False,
                            weights='imagenet',
                            input_tensor=None,
                            input_shape=(IMAGE_SIZE[0],IMAGE_SIZE[1],3))
    
    InceptionBaseOutput = inception_resnet_base_model.output
    InceptionFlattenLayer = Flatten()(InceptionBaseOutput)
    InceptionDropoutLayer = Dropout(0.5)(InceptionFlattenLayer)
    InceptionOutputLayer = Dense(ANIMAL_TYPES, activation='softmax', name='softmax')(InceptionDropoutLayer)
    
    inception_resnet_model = Model(inputs=inception_resnet_base_model.input, outputs=InceptionOutputLayer)
    
    for layer in inception_resnet_model.layers[:INCEPTION_FREEZE_LAYERS]:
        layer.trainable = False
    for layer in inception_resnet_model.layers[INCEPTION_FREEZE_LAYERS:]:
        layer.trainable = True
        
    inception_resnet_model.compile(optimizer=Adam(learning_rate=1e-5),
                      loss='categorical_crossentropy', metrics=['accuracy'])

A similar approach has been taken for the ResNet50 model as well. We are using pre-trained weights here as well and setting the shape as 224x224. Here however, we only freeze 2 layers instead of 3 mentioned in the previous architecture. This brought more optimistic results for this model. The hyper parameters for learning_rate and FREEZE_LAYERS have been set here.

In [ ]:
with tf.device('/gpu:0'):
    FREEZE_LAYERS = 2

    resnet_base_model = ResNet50(include_top=False, weights='imagenet', input_tensor=None,
                   input_shape=(IMAGE_SIZE[0],IMAGE_SIZE[1],3))

    BaseOutput = resnet_base_model.output
    FlattenNetLayer = Flatten()(BaseOutput)
    DropoutNetLayer = Dropout(0.5)(FlattenNetLayer)
    OutputNetLayer = Dense(ANIMAL_TYPES, activation='softmax', name='softmax')(DropoutNetLayer)

    resnet_model = Model(inputs=resnet_base_model.input, outputs=OutputNetLayer)

    for layer in resnet_model.layers[:FREEZE_LAYERS]:
        layer.trainable = False

    for layer in resnet_model.layers[FREEZE_LAYERS:]:
        layer.trainable = True

    resnet_model.compile(optimizer=Adam(learning_rate=1e-5),
                      loss='categorical_crossentropy', metrics=['accuracy'])

This is where image resizing and data augmentation is taking place. Here, we are setting the BATCH_SIZE of 30 after completing multiple iterations and 30 seemed to bring the best results with the least training time. We do multiple image preprocessing functions to improve the accuracy of the model. The train_data_gen mentioned here includes all the pre-processing techniques that have been used for this model. The train_data is then shuffled to make sure the model does not overfit. That is the reason shuffle=True is there on the train_data but it's false on the test_data.

In [ ]:
BATCH_SIZE = 30

train_data_gen = ImageDataGenerator(
    preprocessing_function=preprocess_input,
    rotation_range=40,
    width_shift_range=0.2,
    height_shift_range=0.2,
    shear_range=0.2,
    zoom_range=0.2,
    channel_shift_range=10,
    horizontal_flip=True,
    fill_mode='nearest',
)

train_data = train_data_gen.flow_from_directory(
    directory=train_data_dir,
    target_size=IMAGE_SIZE,
    batch_size=BATCH_SIZE,
    class_mode='categorical',
    shuffle=True,
    subset='training',
    interpolation='bicubic',
)

valid_data_gen = ImageDataGenerator(preprocessing_function=preprocess_input)

test_data  = valid_data_gen.flow_from_directory(
    directory=test_data_dir,
    target_size=IMAGE_SIZE,
    batch_size=BATCH_SIZE,
    class_mode='categorical',
    shuffle=False,
    interpolation='bicubic',
)

Early stopping is applied with a patience of 2. That means if the val_loss does not decrease in 2 epochs, the fitting will stop since the model is not learning anymore. This is to save both time and power resources.

In [ ]:
es = EarlyStopping(monitor='val_loss', patience=2)

Using a GPU we try to fit the model using 15 epochs. We set the es (early_stopping) as a callback and run the model. Here, the early stopping is triggered since the val_loss does not seem to improve much after the 10th epoch. The model is however, able to reach a val_accuracy of 82.42%

In [ ]:
with tf.device('/gpu:0'):
    inception_resnet_history = inception_resnet_model.fit(

        validation_data = test_data,
        epochs = 15,
        steps_per_epoch= len(train_data.filenames)//BATCH_SIZE,
        validation_steps=len(test_data.filenames)//BATCH_SIZE,
        callbacks=[es]
    )

We are doing manual validation of the models here. We are taking images which the model has not seen yet in training or testing for validation and seeing how the model is performing.

We first load the models, use the .predict() function to get the probabilities and from the np.argmax() we take the highest probability and check the name of the class which follows the index of the highest probability. We then show the image along with the class name and the confidence on a subplot.

In [ ]:
sorted_class_names = sorted(class_names)

# Load the model
resnet_trained_model = keras.models.load_model('resnet50_model_1.h5')
inception_resnet_trained_model = keras.models.load_model('inception_resnet_model_1.h5')

# Load the image
img = keras.preprocessing.image.load_img('/wildlife-classification/fish.jpg', target_size=(224, 224))

# Predict the class
resnet_result = resnet_trained_model.predict(keras.preprocessing.image.img_to_array(img).reshape(1, 224, 224, 3))
inception_resnet_result = inception_resnet_trained_model.predict(keras.preprocessing.image.img_to_array(img).reshape(1, 224, 224, 3))

# Get the predicted class
resnet_predicted_class = np.argmax(resnet_result)
inception_resnet_predicted_class = np.argmax(inception_resnet_result)

# Create subplots
fig, axs = plt.subplots(nrows=1, ncols=2, figsize=(10, 5))

# Plot data on first subplot
axs[0].imshow(img)
axs[0].axis('off')
axs[0].set_title('ResNet50 Predicted Class: ' + sorted_class_names[resnet_predicted_class] + '\nProbability: ' + str(round(resnet_result[0][resnet_predicted_class]*100, 2)) + '%')

# Plot data on second subplot
axs[1].imshow(img)
axs[1].axis('off')
axs[1].set_title('Inception ResNet V2 Predicted Class: ' + sorted_class_names[inception_resnet_predicted_class] + '\nProbability: ' + str(round(inception_resnet_result[0][inception_resnet_predicted_class]*100, 2)) + '%')


# Adjust layout and display the plot
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()
